        Let <m>S(n)</m> be the statement that <m>a_n\leq 2</m>.
        Our computations show that <m>S(1)</m> is true.
        Assume that <m>S(k)</m> is true for some <m>k\geq 1</m>,
        that is, <m>a_k\leq 2</m>.
        We consider the statement <m>S(k+1)</m>.
        By definition of the sequence we have
        <me>
          a_{k+1}=\sqrt{2+a_k}
        </me>.
        By the induction hypothesis <m>a_k\leq 2</m>, hence
        <me>
          a_{k+1}\leq \sqrt{2+2}=2
        </me>.
        The statement <m>S(k+1)</m> has been proved and thus we have that
        <m>a_n\leq 2</m> for all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>.
      </p>
