    <li>
      <p>
        <xref ref="proof-cons-3"></xref>
        We can rewrite the equation as
        <me>
          2(2x_1+3x_2)+9x_3=n
        </me>
        and another possibility is as follows
        <me>
          4x_1+3(2x_2+3x_3)=n
        </me>.
        We will use the second form because the largest coefficient is 4 while in case of the first form the largest
        coefficient is 9.
        So we have
        <me>
          4x_1+3y_1=n
        </me>.
        A particular solution is <m>(n,-n)</m>, therefore we get
        <md>
          <mrow>x_1\amp =n+3t,</mrow>
          <mrow>y_1\amp =-n-4t</mrow>
        </md>
        for some <m>t\in\mathbb{Z}</m>.
        We have that <m>y_1=2x_2+3x_3=-n-4t</m>.
        This equation has a particular solution
        <m>(n-2t,-n)</m>, therefore we obtain that
        <md>
          <mrow>x_2\amp =n-2t+3s,</mrow>
          <mrow>x_3\amp =-n-2s</mrow>
        </md>
        for some <m>s,t\in\mathbb{Z}</m>.
        That is, the parametrization of the integral solution of the equation is
        given by
        <md>
          <mrow>x_1\amp =n+3t,</mrow>
          <mrow>x_2\amp =n-2t+3s,</mrow>
          <mrow>x_3\amp =-n-2s</mrow>
        </md>
        for some <m>s,t\in\mathbb{Z}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

